\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\begin_inset Argument item:1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
-
\end_layout

\end_inset

Treatment sites are in optimal locations. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\begin_inset Argument item:1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
-
\end_layout

\end_inset

Treatment sites are of a suitable size to handle the expected wastewater volume from the sources. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The size of the constructed treatment wetlands has to be big enough to serve the amount of wastewater produced, but not too big as the system may collapse due to a lack of nutrients for the plants towards the end of the wetlands. Additionally, the location of the constructed wetlands has to be taken into consideration to determine the shortest distance of pipes required to link the wastewater sources to the treatment area to balance the cost of transporting wastewater and building the site. 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after ""
before ""
key "mawss2015"

\end_inset

 In order to determine the ideal location and size of constructed wetlands in a defined area, a mathematical model has been developed to represent the problem. Solving this model will give the ideal location and size of constructed wetlands to be designed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Process Model for Constructed Wetlands
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Over the years, implementation of more treatment wetlands in addition to higher water quality standards have encouraged studies to focus on establishing process design tools for the wetlands. Of all the types of wetlands that have been implemented, the horizontal sub-surface flow (HSSF) constructed wetlands is one of the most common. 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "rousseau2004model"

\end_inset

 recommends the first-order 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-
\begin_inset Formula $C^*$
\end_inset

 model for representing the constructed wetlands reaction process as it is a good balance between scientific accuracy and complexity as compared to other models that have been developed.
\end_layout

