\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula $z_{jk}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="none" valignment="top" bottomline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Standard
binary variable, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{jk}=1$
\end_inset

 if construction option 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is chosen for site 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 otherwise. In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{j0}$
\end_inset

 denotes the choice of not constructing any CWs in site 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="none" valignment="top" bottomline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
</lyxtabular>

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "table:modelparameter"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before the uncertainty component is addressed, we may come up with a deterministic model to solve the problem first. The objective of the problem is to minimize the total cost of implementing the system in a region. The following constraints formulate the constructed wetlands construction option, wastewater allocation between sources and constructed wetlands, pollutant removal performance, treatment target fulfillment:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Constructed wetlands design options:
\series default
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{jk}$
\end_inset

 be a binary variable that describes the design option 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 selected for the constructed wetlands site 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

. In the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

, there will be no constructed wetlands on the potential site 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

. Otherwise, any other values for 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 will correspond to the respective design options available. When 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{jk} = 1$
\end_inset

, it means that there will be a constructed wetlands of type 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 at site 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

. The different design options result in different construction costs and pollutant removal capacities. To maintain the logic of the problem, only one design option can be selected at each site. Hence, the following constraint is introduced: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation*}
	\begin{split}
	&\sum_{k=0}^{K}z_{jk}=1,~~~\forall j\\
	&z_{jk}\in\{0,1\},~~~\forall j,k
	\end{split}
\end{equation*}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Wastewater allocation from sources to sites:
\series default
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{ij}$
\end_inset

 be a binary variable that describes the interconnection between the wastewater source 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and potential contructed wetlands site 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

. When 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{ij} = 1$
\end_inset

, wastewater is allowed to flow from source 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to site 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

. Otherwise, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{ij} = 0$
\end_inset

. To ensure that the wastewater is allocated consistently, the total of all the flows from a single source 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 should be equal to the flow generated by source 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

. On top of that, the total volume of wastewater flowing into a constructed wetland cannot exceed the design capacity of the constructed wetland. Finally, there should only be wastewater sent to a site if there is a connection (
\begin_inset Formula $y_{ij} = 1$
\end_inset

). If 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{ij}$
\end_inset

 represents the proportion of wastewater sent from source 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to site 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the total wastewater flow from source 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{jk}$
\end_inset

 is the maximum flow capacity accepted by site 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 with design option 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{alignat*}{2}
    &\sum_{i=1}^{I}x_{ij}F_{i}\leq \sum_{k=0}^{K}Q_{jk}z_{jk},~~ &&\forall j\label{eq:CWcapacity}\\
	&\sum_{j=1}^{J}x_{ij}=1, &&\forall i \nonumber\\
	&0 \leq F_ix_{ij}\leq F_iy_{ij},&&\forall i,j\nonumber\\
	& y_{ij}\in\{0,1\}&&\forall i,j\nonumber
\end{alignat*}
\end_inset


\series bold
Pollutant removal performance and treatment target fulfillment:
\series default
 First, we consider the influent of the constructed wetlands. The water that is entering the constructed wetlands should have the same amount of pollutants as all of the sources that are contributing wastewater to the site. To determine the pollutant concentration in the effluent, we use a first-order 
\begin_inset Formula $k-C^*$
\end_inset

 model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after ""
before ""
key "rousseau2004model"

\end_inset

 to calculate the pollutant removal. Finally, to ensure that treatment targets are met, the effluent pollutant concentrations should be subject to treatment target constraints. 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{alignat*}{2}
	&{\sum_{i=1}^{I}F_{i}y_{ij}\varepsilon_{i}^{m}} = \varepsilon_{in,j}^{m}{\sum_{i=1}^{I}F_{i}y_{ij}} &&\forall j,m\\
	&[\varepsilon_{in,j}^{m}-{c}_{j}^{m*}]\sum_{k=0}^{K}e^{-\frac{A_{jk}}{Q_{jk}}k_{A}^{m}}z_{jk}+c_{j}^{m*} = \varepsilon_{out,j}^{m} &&\forall j,m\\
	&\varepsilon_{out,j}^{m}\leq \tau_{j}^{m}~~~&&\forall j\\
\end{alignat*}
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
%The following deterministic model is developed from the above constraints. It is a 
\backslash
emph{Mixed-Integer Linear Programming} (MILP) problem (Model D):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation*}\label{modelD}
\begin{aligned}
	\text{Model D}:~~&min \sum_{i=1}^{I}\sum_{j=1}^{J}d_{ij}c_s x_{ij} + \sum_{j=1}^{J}\sum_{k=1}^{K}c_{cw,jk}y_{jk}\\~~
	\mbox{s.t.}~~
	&\sum_{i=1}^{I} (a_{jk}^m \varepsilon_i^m - b_{ij}^m) z_{ij} - M(1 - y_{jk}) \leq \tau_{net,j}^m \sum_{i=1}^I z_{ij}  && \forall j,k,m\\
 	&\sum_{i=1}^{I} z_{ij} \leq \sum_{k=0}^K Q_{jk} y_{jk} && \forall j\\
	&\sum_{j=1}^J z_{ij} = F_i && \forall i\\
	&z_{ij} \leq F_i x_{ij} && \forall i,j\\
	&x_{ij} + y_{j0} \leq 1 && \forall i,j\\
	&\sum_{k=0}^{K}y_{jk} = 1&&\forall j\\
	&x_{ij} \in \{0,1\}&&\forall i,j\\
	&y_{jk} \in \{0,1\}&&\forall j,k\\
	&z_{ij} \geq 0&&\forall i,j\\
\end{aligned}
\end{equation*}
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Case study: a decentralized CWs system for municipal wastewater treatment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Mobile, Alabama
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With 412,992 people, Mobile County is the second most populated county within the state Alabama in the United States. The population of Mobile County has been steadily increasing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after ""
before ""
key "uscb2002census"

\end_inset

. As populations grow, several fringe communities are created. To manage the wastewater produced by such communities, the traditional approach is to link these fringe communities up with long length large diameter pipes to transport all the wastewater to a single municipal wastewater treatment plant to be processed and then released into nearby water sources. The Mobile Area Water & Sewer System (MAWSS) serves approximately 530 square kilometres in Mobile County 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after ""
before ""
key "mawss2015"

\end_inset

, mostly through centralised wastewater treatment facilities. However, annual operations and maintenance costs for such centralised wastewater management systems have been shown to be costlier than decentralised ones, where the wastewater is processed and released within the community 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after ""
before ""
key "mawss2015"

\end_inset

. Thus, implementation of decentralised wastewater management systems such as constructed wetlands are being considered to manage costs in the long term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Data Collection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case Study Area:
\series default

\begin_inset Float figure
placement !b
wide false
sideways false
status open


\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Graphics 
	filename blocks.png
	width 35text%

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Case study area in Mobile, Alabama.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:blocks"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The site chosen for the case study is near Mobile Regional Airport. It is a suburban area, mostly consisting of residences. As the objective of the project is to show how the optimization model can be applied, we have chosen a smaller area to keep the computation resources required reasonable. Hence, the site has been divided into 14 blocks based on six census tract blocks. The blocks are represented with blue outlines in Fig. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:blocks"

\end_inset

. Geographic information about the region listed in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "table:geodata"

\end_inset

 was also retrieved from the census. 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after ""
before ""
key "acs2015"

\end_inset

 For each block, we have assumed a point source for the wastewater (see red circles).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Potential sites for the constructed wetlands were identified from Google Maps and represented in Fig. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:blocks"

\end_inset

 as green rectangles. These areas are empty and thus the construction of wetlands there will impact few residents negatively. A point location is used to represent each of these sites. The coordinates of the potential sites are stated in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "table:cwdata"

\end_inset

. The distances between the wastewater sources and potential sites were calculated as well and stated in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "table:distdata"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Pollutants:
\series default
 Once again, to keep the model manageable, we have narrowed down the number of pollutants to three, as seen in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "table:polldata"

\end_inset

. The pollutants have been selected based on the effects of pollution if these substances were not removed. In this case study, we will set the treatment target to be the same regardless of the intended use for the treated water.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Design options:
\series default
 We have determined four design options for the constructed wetlands and their respective construction costs can be found in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "table:ccwdata"

\end_inset

. The formula for estimating the cost can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "kadlec2009"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Sewer pipe construction cost:
\series default
 Based on 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "kadlec2009"

\end_inset

, the normal size of sewer pipes for treatment wetlands vary from 
\begin_inset Formula $10-30 cm$
\end_inset

 diameter pipes. Hence, the sewer pipe construction cost is estimated to be about 
\begin_inset Formula $US\$134/m$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after ""
before ""
key "usepa2000"

\end_inset

 after revising to latest prices. 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above information provides a good set-up to determine optimal locations for constructed wetlands to be built within Mobile, Alabama.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Further Directions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proceeding from here, the next step would be to find a solution for the deterministic model, which will be done using MATLAB. After which, work will commence on developing the probabilistic model and running it.
\end_layout

